      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Load the Pretrained Language Model\n",
        "We are first going to look at pretrained language model provided by HuggingFace models. We will use a variant of BERT, called [DistilBERTbase uncased](https://huggingface.co/distilbert/distilbert-base-uncased-finetuned-sst-2-english). This model is a fine-tune checkpoint of DistilBERT-base-uncased, fine-tuned on SST-2.\n",
        "\n",
        "This model is a distilled version of the BERT base model. This model is uncased: it does not make a difference between english and English.\n",
        "\n",
        "Knowledge distillation help to train smaller LMs with similar performance and potential.\n",
        "\n",
        "<!-- The code uses [DistilRoBERTa base model](https://huggingface.co/distilbert/distilroberta-base) [[paper](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1910.01108)], which is a distilled version of the RoBERTa-base model. It follows the same training procedure as DistilBERT.  -->\n",
        "\n",
        "DistilBERT is a transformers model, smaller and faster than BERT, which was pretrained on the same corpus in a self-supervised fashion, using the BERT base model as a teacher. This means it was pretrained on the raw texts only, with no humans labelling them in any way (which is why it can use lots of publicly available data) with an automatic process to generate inputs and labels from those texts using the BERT base model.\n",
        "\n",
        "# TRAINED ON FOLLOWING LOSS FUNCTION\n",
        "\n",
        "## Distillation loss:\n",
        " - trained to return the same probabilities as the BERT base model.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Masked language modeling (MLM):\n",
        " - part of the original training loss of the BERT base model. When taking a sentence, the model randomly masks 15% of the words in the input then run the entire masked sentence through the model and has to predict the masked words.\n",
        "\n",
        " - This is different from traditional recurrent neural networks (RNNs) that usually see the words one after the other, or from autoregressive models like GPT which internally mask the future tokens. It allows the model to learn a bidirectional representation of the sentence.\n",
        "## Cosine embedding loss:\n",
        "the model was also trained to generate hidden states as close as possible as the BERT base model."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "DV1Nqr8OAuBM"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# Tokenization\n",
        "##(https://huggingface.co/transformers/v2.11.0/main_classes/tokenizer.html)\n",
        "is a fundamental concept in natural language processing (NLP), especially when dealing with language models.\n",
        "\n",
        "A tokenizer breaks down raw text into smaller units called tokens. These tokens can represent words, subwords, or characters, depending on the type of tokenizer being used. The goal of tokenization is to convert human-readable text into a form that is more interpretable by machine learning models.\n",
        "\n",
        "Tokenizer processes the text and outputs several key components:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **input_ids**: A list of integer IDs representing the tokens. Each token corresponds to an entry in the model's vocabulary.\n",
        "- **attention_mask**: A list of ones and zeros indicating which tokens should be attended to by the model. This is especially useful when dealing with padding.\n",
        "\n",
        "Two **special tokens**: 101 and 102. These tokens are special markers used by many models to denote the beginning and end of a sentence. Specifically:\n",
        "\n",
        "- 101: Marks the beginning of the sentence.\n",
        "- 102: Marks the end of the sentence.\n",
        "\n",
        "# The attention_mask helps the model distinguish between real tokens and padding tokens.\n",
        "\n",
        "If the attention_mask is a list of ones, all tokens should be attended to.\n",
        "\n",
        "If there were padding tokens, there are zeros in the mask to instruct the model to ignore them"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3Vjrm7DGl6o1"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "#@title UNDERSTANDING TOKENIZATION OF INPUT, CHECKING SENTIMENT ANALYSIS PIPELINE\n",
        "\n",
        "from transformers import pipeline\n",
        "from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification\n",
        "\n",
        "model_name = \"distilbert-base-uncased-finetuned-sst-2-english\"\n",
        "model = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(model_name)\n",
        "tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name)\n",
        "base_model = model.base_model\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create the classifier pipeline\n",
        "classifier = pipeline(\"sentiment-analysis\", model=model, tokenizer=tokenizer)\n",
        "\n",
        "sentence = \"Speak friend, and enter !\"\n",
        "\n",
        "res = tokenizer(sentence)\n",
        "print(res)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "out = model(torch.tensor(res[\"input_ids\"]).unsqueeze(0), torch.tensor(res[\"attention_mask\"]).unsqueeze(0))\n",
        "# out = model(torch.tensor(res), torch.tensor(res))\n",
        "print(out)\n",
        "\n",
        "tokens = tokenizer.tokenize(sentence)\n",
        "print(tokens)\n",
        "\n",
        "ids = tokenizer.convert_tokens_to_ids(tokens)\n",
        "print(ids)\n",
        "\n",
        "decoded_string = tokenizer.decode(ids)\n",
        "print(decoded_string)"
      ],
